3. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW

3.1 Holistic Architecture: 5-Layer Model

QUENNE employs a hierarchical, distributed architecture across five layers:

```
LAYER 5: COSMIC CONSCIOUSNESS
├── Collective Intelligence Framework
├── Consciousness Preservation System
├── Universal Knowledge Repository
└── Post-Biological Evolution Pathway

LAYER 4: INTERSTELLAR EXPANSION
├── Starlane Communication Network
├── Von Neumann Probes
├── Dyson Swarm Construction
└── Exoplanet Settlement Infrastructure

LAYER 3: PHYSICAL INFRASTRUCTURE
├── Astral-Class Starship Fleet
├── Humanoid Robot Swarms
├── Orbital Manufacturing Facilities
├── Space-Based Power Stations
└── Planetary Surface Bases

LAYER 2: COSMIC MIND AI ECOSYSTEM
├── 12 Foundation AI Models
├── Quantum-Enhanced Training Infrastructure
├── Multi-Modal Inference Engine
└── Ethical Governance Framework

LAYER 1: COSMIC-SCALE OPERATING SYSTEM (QAOS)
├── Quantum-Hardened Microkernel
├── Distributed Intelligence Layer
├── Consciousness Integration
└── Security & Governance

LAYER 0: QUANTUM-ENTANGLED NETWORK
├── 1024× QUENNE Satellite Constellation
├── Quantum Internet Backbone
├── Interplanetary Communication Network
└── Quantum Memory Cloud
```

3.2 Constellation Design and Orbital Mechanics

Orbital Parameters:

· Orbit: Medium Earth Orbit (MEO)
· Altitude: 10,000 km
· Inclination: 55° (global coverage)
· Period: 5.8 hours
· Constellation Size: 1024 satellites
· Orbital Planes: 32 planes with 32 satellites each
· Inter-satellite spacing: ~1,000 km
· Coverage: Minimum 4 satellites visible from any Earth point
· Latency: <50 ms satellite-to-satellite, <200 ms end-to-end

Constellation Management:

· Autonomous Coordination: Swarm intelligence algorithms
· Self-Healing: Automatic reconfiguration after satellite loss
· Load Balancing: Dynamic task distribution based on capability and position
· Collision Avoidance: Automated with space situational awareness
· Orbital Maintenance: ΔV budget 50 m/s per year

Expansion Phases:

· Phase 3 (2033-2037): 144 satellites (12 planes × 12 satellites)
· Phase 4 (2038-2047): 1024 satellites (32 planes × 32 satellites)
· Phase 5 (2048+): Additional orbits (GEO, HEO, lunar, interplanetary)

3.3 Ground Segment Architecture

Primary Ground Stations (3):

· Equatorial Station 1: Kourou, French Guiana (5°N)
· Equatorial Station 2: Tanegashima, Japan (30°N)
· Polar Station: Svalbard, Norway (78°N)

Secondary Ground Stations (12):

· Distributed globally for redundancy and low-latency access
· Each station: 2× 10m antennas, X/Ka-band
· Data rate: 10 Gbps per link

Quantum Ground Stations (6):

· High-altitude, low-turbulence sites
· 1m telescopes with adaptive optics
· Superconducting nanowire single-photon detectors
· Quantum key distribution at 1 Mbps

Mission Control Centers:

· Primary: QUENNE Headquarters, Asaka City, Japan
· Backup 1: Houston, Texas, USA
· Backup 2: Geneva, Switzerland
· Backup 3: Singapore

Network Operations Center:

· 24/7 monitoring with AI-assisted operations
· 100 operators (initial), reducing to 50 with autonomy
· Predictive maintenance coordination
· Security monitoring and response

3.4 Network Topology and Communication

Physical Topology:

· Intra-satellite: Optical mesh with 400 Gbps links
· Inter-satellite: Free-space optical with 1 Tbps links
· Satellite-to-ground: Optical (100 Gbps) + RF (10 Gbps)
· Quantum network: Entanglement distribution with quantum repeaters

Logical Topology:

· Overlay Network: Virtual topology optimized for application needs
· Content Delivery: Edge computing with data localization
· Service Mesh: Microservices architecture across constellation
· Blockchain Layer: Distributed ledger for coordination and security

Protocol Stack:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 7: Application                       │
