3.5 Data Flow and Processing Pipeline

Ingestion Paths:

1. Earth Observation: Direct from satellite sensors (optical, SAR, hyperspectral)
2. Scientific Data: From space telescopes and instruments (astronomy, particle physics)
3. User Computation: From ground stations and internet (research, commercial)
4. Interplanetary Data: From deep space probes and other planetary missions

Processing Pipeline:

```
Raw Data → Quantum Preprocessing → Neuromorphic Pattern Recognition
     ↓                                    ↓
Classical Filtering               Feature Extraction
     ↓                                    ↓
Storage Tiering                   Model Training
     ↓                                    ↓
Archive Storage                   Inference Serving
```

Storage Hierarchy:

· Level 0: Sensor buffers (1 TB, 10 ms access)
· Level 1: Processing memory (2 TB, 100 ns access)
· Level 2: Working storage (50 TB, 10 μs access)
· Level 3: Archive storage (500 TB, 100 ms access)
· Level 4: Quantum holographic (1 PB, 1 s access)

Data Distribution:

· Replication: 3× across constellation for durability
· Sharding: Horizontal partitioning across satellites
· Caching: Predictive caching based on access patterns
· Migration: Automatic data movement based on usage

3.6 Control Hierarchy and Autonomy Levels

Autonomous Control Levels:

```
Level 4: Constellation Objectives (Human input)
         │
Level 3: Mission Planning (AI optimization)
         │
Level 2: Satellite Coordination (Swarm algorithms)
         │
Level 1: Subsystem Control (Local autonomy)
         │
Level 0: Component Control (Real-time feedback)
```

Human-in-the-Loop:

· Strategic: Goal setting and priority allocation
· Tactical: Exception handling and override capability
· Monitoring: Situational awareness and trend analysis
· Ethical Oversight: Value alignment verification

AI Autonomy:

· Reactive: Real-time response to events
· Predictive: Anticipation of future states
· Adaptive: Learning from experience
· Evolutionary: Self-improvement over time

Control Interfaces:

· Direct Control: Manual command for emergencies
· Supervisory Control: High-level objective specification
· Collaborative Control: Human-AI joint decision making
· Autonomous Control: Full AI operation with human oversight

Decision Quality Metrics:

· Completeness: All relevant factors considered
· Accuracy: Based on correct information
· Timeliness: Decision made in appropriate timeframe
· Robustness: Works under range of conditions
· Ethical Soundness: Aligns with ethical principles

